english:
  title: On the Names of the Lee Brothers
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Two brothers of the Lee family came to me seeking characters for their names. The elder I called Yeop (與點), meaning 'to befriend the ancients,' and the younger I called Sajeom (思點), meaning 'to aspire to noble purpose.' And I spoke to them thus:

    Once Zengzi walked with five or six youths and six or seven children. They bathed in the waters of Yi, felt the wind upon the terrace of Wu, singing as they returned. This was the heart of Zengzi—to find joy in the fellowship of friends. Confucius sighed deeply and said, 'I approve of Zengzi alone.' This was Zengzi's aspiration, one which harmonized with the wisdom of the sage. For the sage takes heaven and earth as his body, allowing all things to perfect their true nature. The aspiration of the sage is the very heart of heaven and earth. How then could Zengzi's aspiration accord with this?

    It was because Zengzi's learning had reached great heights. His spirit was serene and untroubled; his demeanor calm and composed. The principles of heaven moved constantly through his daily life, while human desires had ceased within his thoughts. Thus could he walk with youths and children, singing homeward through the gentle spring wind and warm air, sharing in their joy. High and low had found their proper place; self and world became one without boundary. All was orderly, all was harmonious. His ease was graceful, his bearing noble and luminous—as if reflecting that celestial virtue which gives comfort to the aged, trust to friends, and nurture to the young. His joy transcended not the ordinary moments of friendship and daily life, yet his purpose harmonized with the great way of sages and heaven-and-earth.

    Ah, scholars born in ages hence must befriend the ancients above them. Those who lack position must cherish the aspiration to noble purpose. Should not such befriending be with the disciples of the sage? Should not such aspiration be the aspiration of the virtuous?

    If a learner can expand the heart and settle the body, clearing the mind of even the smallest obstruction, rising above all things, then a transcendent spirit will bloom—joy accumulating within like clouds rising outward, manifesting in every gesture and silence, in every moment of wind-song and moon-gazing. In such moments, one may suddenly feel: 'I too approve of Zengzi.' Though a thousand years separate us, we may stand as equals. Yeop, should you not befriend the ancients?

    Yet to achieve this, there is a root. Without humanity, there is no dwelling; without righteousness, no action. In stillness, maintain vigilance and restraint; in movement, observe carefully and act with caution. Let the principles of heaven ever abide while human desires never arise. In all daily conduct, let nothing be amiss. Whether in poverty or prosperity, sorrow or joy, obtain fulfillment everywhere. Above, feel no shame before heaven; below, harbor no embarrassment before others. Then the heart rests in peace, and joy naturally flows. Though the sages are distant, you may walk the same path with them.

    But if purpose be set low and effort grow slack, heaven's principles fade daily while human desires burn ever brighter. Your body and mind become servants to external things—laboring endlessly in anxiety, worrying constantly in distress. Though you might taste fleeting pleasures, you would only fear their loss, having no leisure to tend your own nature. How then could you extend this to friends? Your heart grown small, how could you aspire to the virtuous?

    Therefore, purpose must be set high. Sajeom, should you not aspire to noble purpose? Take the aspiration of the virtuous as your own; take the learning of the virtuous as your own. Thus you may befriend the ancients. Yet know this: Zengzi was one of daring spirit, sometimes faltering in deed. To attain Zengzi's vision while avoiding his shortcomings depends upon setting your purpose high and cultivating your learning well. Ah, you two brothers—strive with all your might!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yeop (與點) and Zengzi (曾點) are the same person—a legendary disciple of Confucius. The name-giving here creates a poetic resonance between the brother's character and this ancient sage.
  - key: ''
    value: The passage about bathing in Yi and the wind at Wu references the Analects 11.26, where Zengzi describes his ideal of life in harmony with nature and friends.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'I approve of Zengzi' (吾與點也) is Confucius's highest praise, indicating perfect alignment between personal aspiration and universal principles.
  - key: ''
    value: Kwon Geun employs Neo-Confucian philosophy throughout, particularly the concepts of 天理 (heavenly principles) and 人欲 (human desires), reflecting the moral cultivation central to Song-Ming thought.
